en_807780_0	Robert Mugabe, Zimbabwe’s first post-independence leader, has died aged 95.Mr Mugabe had been receiving treatment in a hospital in Singapore since April.He was ousted in a military coup in 2017 after 37 years in power.
en_807780_1	Mr Mugabe’s early years were praised for broadening access to health and education for the black majority – but his later years were marked by rights abuses and corruption.
en_807780_2	He won Zimbabwe’s first election after it secured independence from the UK, becoming prime minister in 1980.
en_807780_3	He abolished the office in 1987, becoming president instead.Mr Mugabe was born on 21 February 1924 in what was then Rhodesia.
en_807780_4	The country, once a British colony, was run by a white minority.Mr Mugabe, with his high profile in the independence movement, secured an overwhelming victory in the republic’s first election.
